[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] In electrical engineering, statistical computing and bioinformatics, the **Baum–Welch algorithm** is a special case of the expectation–maximization algorithm used to find the unknown parameters of a hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] It makes use of the forward-backward algorithm to compute the statistics for the expectation step.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The Baum–Welch algorithm, the primary method for inference in hidden Markov models, is numerically unstable due to its recursive calculation of joint probabilities.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] As the number of variables grows, these joint probabilities become increasingly small, leading to the forward recursions rapidly approaching values below machine precision.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The Baum–Welch algorithm was named after its inventors Leonard E.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The algorithm and the Hidden Markov models were first described in a series of articles by Baum and his peers at the IDA Center for Communications Research, Princeton in the late 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] One of the first major applications of HMMs was to the field of speech processing.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] In the 1980s, HMMs were emerging as a useful tool in the analysis of biological systems and information, and in particular genetic information.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] They have since become an important tool in the probabilistic modeling of genomic sequences.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] A hidden Markov model describes the joint probability of a collection of "hidden" and observed discrete random variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] It relies on the assumption that the *i*-th hidden variable given the (*i* − 1)-th hidden variable is independent of previous hidden variables, and the current observation variables depend only on the current hidden state.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The Baum–Welch algorithm uses the well known EM algorithm to find the maximum likelihood estimate of the parameters of a hidden Markov model given a set of observed feature vectors.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Let $X_{t}$ be a discrete hidden random variable with N possible values (i.e.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The observation variables $Y_{t}$ can take one of K possible values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] We also assume the observation given the "hidden" state is time independent.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Taking into account all the possible values of $Y_{t}$ and $X_{t}$ , we obtain the $N\times K$ matrix $B=\{b_{j}(y_{i})\}$ where $b_{j}$ belongs to all the possible states and $y_{i}$ belongs to all the observations.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Thus we can describe a hidden Markov chain by $\theta =(A,B,\pi )$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The Baum–Welch algorithm finds a local maximum for $\theta ^{*}=\operatorname {arg\,max} _{\theta }P(Y\mid \theta )$ (i.e. the HMM parameters $\theta$ that maximize the probability of the observation).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Set $\theta =(A,B,\pi )$ with random initial conditions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] They can also be set using prior information about the parameters if it is available; this can speed up the algorithm and also steer it toward the desired local maximum.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Since this series converges exponentially to zero, the algorithm will numerically underflow for longer sequences.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] However, this can be avoided in a slightly modified algorithm by scaling $\alpha$ in the forward and $\beta$ in the backward procedure below.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Let $\beta _{i}(t)=P(Y_{t+1}=y_{t+1},\ldots ,Y_{T}=y_{T}\mid X_{t}=i,\theta )$ that is the probability of the ending partial sequence $y_{t+1},\ldots ,y_{T}$ given starting state i at time t .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] which is the probability of being in state i and j at times t and $t+1$ respectively given the observed sequence Y and parameters $\theta$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The denominators of $\gamma _{i}(t)$ and $\xi _{ij}(t)$ are the same ; they represent the probability of making the observation Y given the parameters $\theta$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] which is the expected frequency spent in state i at time 1 .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] which is the expected number of transitions from state *i* to state *j* compared to the expected total number of transitions starting in state *i*, including from state *i* to itself.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The number of transitions starting in state *i* is equivalent to the number of times state *i* is observed in the sequence from *t* = 1 to *t* = *T* − 1.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] is an indicator function, and $b_{i}^{*}(v_{k})$ is the expected number of times the output observations have been equal to $v_{k}$ while in state i over the expected total number of times in state i .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] These steps are now repeated iteratively until a desired level of convergence.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The algorithm described thus far assumes a single observed sequence $Y=y_{1},\ldots ,y_{T}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] However, in many situations, there are several sequences observed: $Y_{1},\ldots ,Y_{R}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] In this case, the information from all of the observed sequences must be used in the update of the parameters A , $\pi$ , and b .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Suppose we have a chicken from which we collect eggs at noon every day.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Now whether or not the chicken has laid eggs for collection depends on some unknown factors that are hidden.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] We can however (for simplicity) assume that the chicken is always in one of two states that influence whether the chicken lays eggs, and that this state only depends on the state on the previous day.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Now we don't know the state at the initial starting point, we don't know the transition probabilities between the two states and we don't know the probability that the chicken lays an egg given a particular state.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] To start we first guess the transition and emission matrices.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The next step is to estimate a new transition matrix.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Thus the new estimate for the ⁠ $S_{1}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $S_{2}$ ⁠ transition is now ${\frac {0.22}{2.4234}}=0.0908$ (referred to as "Pseudo probabilities" in the following tables).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] We then calculate the ⁠ $S_{2}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $S_{1}$ ⁠, ⁠ $S_{2}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $S_{2}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $S_{1}$ ⁠ to ⁠ $S_{1}$ ⁠ transition probabilities and normalize each row of the transition matrix so that the probabilities of transitions from a given starting state sum to 1.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] This allows us to calculate the emission matrix as described above in the algorithm, by adding up the probabilities for the respective observed sequences.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] We then repeat for if N came from ⁠ $S_{1}$ ⁠ and for if N and E came from ⁠ $S_{2}$ ⁠ and normalize.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] To estimate the initial probabilities we assume all sequences start with the hidden state ⁠ $S_{1}$ ⁠ and calculate the highest probability and then repeat for ⁠ $S_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Again we then normalize to give an updated initial vector.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Finally we repeat these steps until the resulting probabilities converge satisfactorily.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Hidden Markov Models were first applied to speech recognition by James K.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Continuous speech recognition occurs by the following steps, modeled by a HMM.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Feature analysis is first undertaken on temporal and/or spectral features of the speech signal.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The feature is then compared to all sequences of the speech recognition units.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] These units could be phonemes, syllables, or whole-word units.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] A lexicon decoding system is applied to constrain the paths investigated, so only words in the system's lexicon (word dictionary) are investigated.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Similar to the lexicon decoding, the system path is further constrained by the rules of grammar and syntax.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Finally, semantic analysis is applied and the system outputs the recognized utterance.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] A limitation of many HMM applications to speech recognition is that the current state only depends on the state at the previous time-step, which is unrealistic for speech as dependencies are often several time-steps in duration.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The Baum–Welch algorithm also has extensive applications in solving HMMs used in the field of speech synthesis.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The Baum–Welch algorithm is often used to estimate the parameters of HMMs in deciphering hidden or noisy information and consequently is often used in cryptanalysis.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] In data security an observer would like to extract information from a data stream without knowing all the parameters of the transmission.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] This can involve reverse engineering a channel encoder.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] HMMs and as a consequence the Baum–Welch algorithm have also been used to identify spoken phrases in encrypted VoIP calls.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] In addition HMM cryptanalysis is an important tool for automated investigations of cache-timing data.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] It allows for the automatic discovery of critical algorithm state, for example key values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The GLIMMER (Gene Locator and Interpolated Markov ModelER) software was an early gene-finding program used for the identification of coding regions in prokaryotic DNA.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] GLIMMER uses Interpolated Markov Models (IMMs) to identify the coding regions and distinguish them from the noncoding DNA.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The latest release (GLIMMER3) has been shown to have increased specificity and accuracy compared with its predecessors with regard to predicting translation initiation sites, demonstrating an average 99% accuracy in locating 3' locations compared to confirmed genes in prokaryotes.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] The GENSCAN webserver is a gene locator capable of analyzing eukaryotic sequences up to one million base-pairs (1 Mbp) long.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] GENSCAN utilizes a general inhomogeneous, three periodic, fifth order Markov model of DNA coding regions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Additionally, this model accounts for differences in gene density and structure (such as intron lengths) that occur in different isochores.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] While most integrated gene-finding software (at the time of GENSCANs release) assumed input sequences contained exactly one gene, GENSCAN solves a general case where partial, complete, or multiple genes (or even no gene at all) is present.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] GENSCAN was shown to exactly predict exon location with 90% accuracy with 80% specificity compared to an annotated database.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Copy-number variations (CNVs) are an abundant form of genome structure variation in humans.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] A discrete-valued bivariate HMM (dbHMM) was used assigning chromosomal regions to seven distinct states: unaffected regions, deletions, duplications and four transition states.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] Solving this model using Baum-Welch demonstrated the ability to predict the location of CNV breakpoint to approximately 300 bp from micro-array experiments.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] This magnitude of resolution enables more precise correlations between different CNVs and across populations than previously possible, allowing the study of CNV population frequencies.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/baum-welch-algorithm] It also demonstrated a direct inheritance pattern for a particular CNV.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In statistics, an **expectation–maximization** (**EM**) **algorithm** is an iterative method to find (local) maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimates of parameters in statistical models, where the model depends on unobserved latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] These parameter-estimates are then used to determine the distribution of the latent variables in the next E step.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It can be used, for example, to estimate a mixture of gaussians, or to solve the multiple linear regression problem.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm was explained and given its name in a classic 1977 paper by Arthur Dempster, Nan Laird, and Donald Rubin.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] They pointed out that the method had been "proposed many times in special circumstances" by earlier authors.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] One of the earliest is the gene-counting method for estimating allele frequencies by Cedric Smith.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hartley in 1958, and Hartley and Hocking in 1977, from which many of the ideas in the Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper originated.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Another one by S.K Ng, Thriyambakam Krishnan and G.J McLachlan in 1977.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hartley's ideas can be broadened to any grouped discrete distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A very detailed treatment of the EM method for exponential families was published by Rolf Sundberg in his thesis and several papers, following his collaboration with Per Martin-Löf and Anders Martin-Löf.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper in 1977 generalized the method and sketched a convergence analysis for a wider class of problems.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Dempster–Laird–Rubin paper established the EM method as an important tool of statistical analysis.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The convergence analysis of the Dempster–Laird–Rubin algorithm was flawed and a correct convergence analysis was published by C.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Wu's proof established the EM method's convergence also outside of the exponential family, as claimed by Dempster–Laird–Rubin.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm is used to find (local) maximum likelihood parameters of a statistical model in cases where the equations cannot be solved directly.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Typically these models involve latent variables in addition to unknown parameters and known data observations.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] That is, either missing values exist among the data, or the model can be formulated more simply by assuming the existence of further unobserved data points.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For example, a mixture model can be described more simply by assuming that each observed data point has a corresponding unobserved data point, or latent variable, specifying the mixture component to which each data point belongs.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Finding a maximum likelihood solution typically requires taking the derivatives of the likelihood function with respect to all the unknown values, the parameters and the latent variables, and simultaneously solving the resulting equations.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In statistical models with latent variables, this is usually impossible.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Instead, the result is typically a set of interlocking equations in which the solution to the parameters requires the values of the latent variables and vice versa, but substituting one set of equations into the other produces an unsolvable equation.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm proceeds from the observation that there is a way to solve these two sets of equations numerically.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] One can simply pick arbitrary values for one of the two sets of unknowns, use them to estimate the second set, then use these new values to find a better estimate of the first set, and then keep alternating between the two until the resulting values both converge to fixed points.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It's not obvious that this will work, but it can be proven in this context.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Additionally, it can be proven that the derivative of the likelihood is (arbitrarily close to) zero at that point, which in turn means that the point is either a local maximum or a saddle point.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In general, multiple maxima may occur, with no guarantee that the global maximum will be found.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Some likelihoods also have singularities in them, i.e., nonsensical maxima.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For example, one of the *solutions* that may be found by EM in a mixture model involves setting one of the components to have zero variance and the mean parameter for the same component to be equal to one of the data points.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, this quantity is often intractable since $\mathbf {Z}$ is unobserved and the distribution of $\mathbf {Z}$ is unknown before attaining ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The missing values (aka latent variables) $\mathbf {Z}$ are discrete, drawn from a fixed number of values, and with one latent variable per observed unit.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The parameters are continuous, and are of two kinds: Parameters that are associated with all data points, and those associated with a specific value of a latent variable (i.e., associated with all data points whose corresponding latent variable has that value).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, it is possible to apply EM to other sorts of models.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Compute the probability of each possible value of ⁠ $\mathbf {Z}$ ⁠, given ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ ⁠.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Then, use the just-computed values of $\mathbf {Z}$ to compute a better estimate for the parameters ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ ⁠.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Iterate steps 2 and 3 until convergence.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The algorithm as just described monotonically approaches a local minimum of the cost function.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Although an EM iteration does increase the observed data (i.e., marginal) likelihood function, no guarantee exists that the sequence converges to a maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For multimodal distributions, this means that an EM algorithm may converge to a local maximum of the observed data likelihood function, depending on starting values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A variety of heuristic or metaheuristic approaches exist to escape a local maximum, such as random-restart hill climbing (starting with several different random initial estimates ⁠ ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}^{(t)}$ ⁠), or applying simulated annealing methods.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM is especially useful when the likelihood is an exponential family, see Sundberg (2019, Ch.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] 8) for a comprehensive treatment: the E step becomes the sum of expectations of sufficient statistics, and the M step involves maximizing a linear function.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In such a case, it is usually possible to derive closed-form expression updates for each step, using the Sundberg formula (proved and published by Rolf Sundberg, based on unpublished results of Per Martin-Löf and Anders Martin-Löf).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM method was modified to compute maximum a posteriori (MAP) estimates for Bayesian inference in the original paper by Dempster, Laird, and Rubin.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Other methods exist to find maximum likelihood estimates, such as gradient descent, conjugate gradient, or variants of the Gauss–Newton algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Unlike EM, such methods typically require the evaluation of first and/or second derivatives of the likelihood function.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Expectation-Maximization works to improve $Q({\boldsymbol {\theta }}\mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }}^{(t)})$ rather than directly improving $\log p(\mathbf {X} \mid {\boldsymbol {\theta }})$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Here it is shown that improvements to the former imply improvements to the latter.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm can be viewed as two alternating maximization steps, that is, as an example of coordinate descent.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Consider the function: $F(q,\theta ):=\operatorname {E} _{q}[\log L(\theta ;x,Z)]+H(q),$ where q is an arbitrary probability distribution over the unobserved data z and *H*(*q*) is the entropy of the distribution q.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A Kalman filter is typically used for on-line state estimation and a minimum-variance smoother may be employed for off-line or batch state estimation.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] However, these minimum-variance solutions require estimates of the state-space model parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM algorithms can be used for solving joint state and parameter estimation problems.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Operate a Kalman filter or a minimum-variance smoother designed with current parameter estimates to obtain updated state estimates.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Use the filtered or smoothed state estimates within maximum-likelihood calculations to obtain updated parameter estimates.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Suppose that a Kalman filter or minimum-variance smoother operates on measurements of a single-input-single-output system that possess additive white noise.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where ${\widehat {x}}_{k}$ are scalar output estimates calculated by a filter or a smoother from N scalar measurements $z_{k}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The above update can also be applied to updating a Poisson measurement noise intensity.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] where ${\widehat {x}}_{k}$ and ${\widehat {x}}_{k+1}$ are scalar state estimates calculated by a filter or a smoother.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The convergence of parameter estimates such as those above are well studied.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A number of methods have been proposed to accelerate the sometimes slow convergence of the EM algorithm, such as those using conjugate gradient and modified Newton's methods (Newton–Raphson).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Also, EM can be used with constrained estimation methods.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This idea is further extended in *generalized expectation maximization (GEM)* algorithm, in which is sought only an increase in the objective function F for both the E step and M step as described in the As a maximization–maximization procedure section.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] GEM is further developed in a distributed environment and shows promising results.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It is also possible to consider the EM algorithm as a subclass of the **MM** (Majorize/Minimize or Minorize/Maximize, depending on context) algorithm, and therefore use any machinery developed in the more general case.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Q-function used in the EM algorithm is based on the log likelihood.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Therefore, it is regarded as the log-EM algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The use of the log likelihood can be generalized to that of the α-log likelihood ratio.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Then, the α-log likelihood ratio of the observed data can be exactly expressed as equality by using the Q-function of the α-log likelihood ratio and the α-divergence.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Obtaining this Q-function is a generalized E step.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Its maximization is a generalized M step.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] This pair is called the α-EM algorithm which contains the log-EM algorithm as its subclass.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Thus, the α-EM algorithm by Yasuo Matsuyama is an exact generalization of the log-EM algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] No computation of gradient or Hessian matrix is needed.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The α-EM shows faster convergence than the log-EM algorithm by choosing an appropriate α.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The α-EM algorithm leads to a faster version of the Hidden Markov model estimation algorithm α-HMM.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM is a partially non-Bayesian, maximum likelihood method.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Its final result gives a probability distribution over the latent variables (in the Bayesian style) together with a point estimate for θ (either a maximum likelihood estimate or a posterior mode).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] A fully Bayesian version of this may be wanted, giving a probability distribution over θ and the latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The Bayesian approach to inference is simply to treat θ as another latent variable.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] In this paradigm, the distinction between the E and M steps disappears.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] If using the factorized Q approximation as described above (variational Bayes), solving can iterate over each latent variable (now including θ) and optimize them one at a time.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Now, k steps per iteration are needed, where k is the number of latent variables.
