[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] The EM algorithm has been implemented in the case where an underlying linear regression model exists explaining the variation of some quantity, but where the values actually observed are censored or truncated versions of those represented in the model.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Special cases of this model include censored or truncated observations from one normal distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] EM typically converges to a local optimum, not necessarily the global optimum, with no bound on the convergence rate in general.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] It is possible that it can be arbitrarily poor in high dimensions and there can be an exponential number of local optima.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Hence, a need exists for alternative methods for guaranteed learning, especially in the high-dimensional setting.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Alternatives to EM exist with better guarantees for consistency, which are termed *moment-based approaches* or the so-called *spectral techniques*.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Moment-based approaches to learning the parameters of a probabilistic model enjoy guarantees such as global convergence under certain conditions unlike EM which is often plagued by the issue of getting stuck in local optima.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] Algorithms with guarantees for learning can be derived for a number of important models such as mixture models, HMMs etc.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/expectation-maximization-algorithm] For these spectral methods, no spurious local optima occur, and the true parameters can be consistently estimated under some regularity conditions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In statistics, a **mixture model** is a probabilistic model for representing the presence of subpopulations within an overall population, without requiring that an observed data set should identify the sub-population to which an individual observation belongs.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Formally a mixture model corresponds to the mixture distribution that represents the probability distribution of observations in the overall population.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models are used for clustering, under the name model-based clustering, and also for density estimation.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models should not be confused with models for compositional data, i.e., data whose components are constrained to sum to a constant value (1, 100%, etc.).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] However, compositional models can be thought of as mixture models, where members of the population are sampled at random.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Conversely, mixture models can be thought of as compositional models, where the total size reading population has been normalized to 1.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In addition, in a Bayesian setting, the mixture weights and parameters will themselves be random variables, and prior distributions will be placed over the variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In such a case, the weights are typically viewed as a *K*-dimensional random vector drawn from a Dirichlet distribution (the conjugate prior of the categorical distribution), and the parameters will be distributed according to their respective conjugate priors.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] This characterization uses *F* and *H* to describe arbitrary distributions over observations and parameters, respectively.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Typically *H* will be the conjugate prior of *F*.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The two most common choices of *F* are Gaussian aka "normal" (for real-valued observations) and categorical (for discrete observations).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] A Bayesian Gaussian mixture model is commonly extended to fit a vector of unknown parameters (denoted in bold), or multivariate normal distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] To incorporate this prior into a Bayesian estimation, the prior is multiplied with the known distribution $p({\boldsymbol {x|\theta }})$ of the data ${\boldsymbol {x}}$ conditioned on the parameters ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ to be estimated.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Although EM-based parameter updates are well-established, providing the initial estimates for these parameters is currently an area of active research.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Note that this formulation yields a closed-form solution to the complete posterior distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Estimations of the random variable ${\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ may be obtained via one of several estimators, such as the mean or maximum of the posterior distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Such distributions are useful for assuming patch-wise shapes of images and clusters, for example.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In the case of image representation, each Gaussian may be tilted, expanded, and warped according to the covariance matrices ${\boldsymbol {\Sigma }}_{i}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] One Gaussian distribution of the set is fit to each patch (usually of size 8×8 pixels) in the image.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Notably, any distribution of points around a cluster (see *k*-means) may be accurately given enough Gaussian components, but scarcely over *K*=20 components are needed to accurately model a given image distribution or cluster of data.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Financial returns often behave differently in normal situations and during crisis times.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] A mixture model for return data seems reasonable.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Sometimes the model used is a jump-diffusion model, or as a mixture of two normal distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] See Financial economics § Challenges and criticism and Financial risk management § Banking for further context.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Assume that we observe the prices of *N* different houses.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Different types of houses in different neighborhoods will have vastly different prices, but the price of a particular type of house in a particular neighborhood (e.g., three-bedroom house in moderately upscale neighborhood) will tend to cluster fairly closely around the mean.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Fitting this model to observed prices, e.g., using the expectation-maximization algorithm, would tend to cluster the prices according to house type/neighborhood and reveal the spread of prices in each type/neighborhood.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Assume that a document is composed of *N* different words from a total vocabulary of size *V*, where each word corresponds to one of *K* possible topics.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The distribution of such words could be modelled as a mixture of *K* different *V*-dimensional categorical distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] A model of this sort is commonly termed a topic model.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Note that expectation maximization applied to such a model will typically fail to produce realistic results, due (among other things) to the excessive number of parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Some sorts of additional assumptions are typically necessary to get good results.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Some sort of additional constraint is placed over the topic identities of words, to take advantage of natural clustering.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The following example is based on an example in Christopher M.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Bishop, *Pattern Recognition and Machine Learning*.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Imagine that we are given an *N*×*N* black-and-white image that is known to be a scan of a hand-written digit between 0 and 9, but we don't know which digit is written.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] We can create a mixture model with $K=10$ different components, where each component is a vector of size $N^{2}$ of Bernoulli distributions (one per pixel).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Such a model can be trained with the expectation-maximization algorithm on an unlabeled set of hand-written digits, and will effectively cluster the images according to the digit being written.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The same model could then be used to recognize the digit of another image simply by holding the parameters constant, computing the probability of the new image for each possible digit (a trivial calculation), and returning the digit that generated the highest probability.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models apply in the problem of directing multiple projectiles at a target (as in air, land, or sea defense applications), where the physical and/or statistical characteristics of the projectiles differ within the multiple projectiles.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] An example might be shots from multiple munitions types or shots from multiple locations directed at one target.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The combination of projectile types may be characterized as a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Further, a well-known measure of accuracy for a group of projectiles is the circular error probable (CEP), which is the number *R* such that, on average, half of the group of projectiles falls within the circle of radius *R* about the target point.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model can be used to determine (or estimate) the value *R*.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model properly captures the different types of projectiles.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The financial example above is one direct application of the mixture model, a situation in which we assume an underlying mechanism so that each observation belongs to one of some number of different sources or categories.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] This underlying mechanism may or may not, however, be observable.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In this form of mixture, each of the sources is described by a component probability density function, and its mixture weight is the probability that an observation comes from this component.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In an indirect application of the mixture model we do not assume such a mechanism.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model is simply used for its mathematical flexibilities.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] For example, a mixture of two normal distributions with different means may result in a density with two modes, which is not modeled by standard parametric distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Another example is given by the possibility of mixture distributions to model fatter tails than the basic Gaussian ones, so as to be a candidate for modeling more extreme events.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixture model-based clustering is also predominantly used in identifying the state of the machine in predictive maintenance.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Density plots are used to analyze the density of high dimensional features.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] If multi-model densities are observed, then it is assumed that a finite set of densities are formed by a finite set of normal mixtures.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] A multivariate Gaussian mixture model is used to cluster the feature data into k number of groups where k represents each state of the machine.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The machine state can be a normal state, power off state, or faulty state.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Each formed cluster can be diagnosed using techniques such as spectral analysis.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In the recent years, this has also been widely used in other areas such as early fault detection.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In image processing and computer vision, traditional image segmentation models often assign to one pixel only one exclusive pattern.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In fuzzy or soft segmentation, any pattern can have certain "ownership" over any single pixel.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] If the patterns are Gaussian, fuzzy segmentation naturally results in Gaussian mixtures.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Combined with other analytic or geometric tools (e.g., phase transitions over diffusive boundaries), such spatially regularized mixture models could lead to more realistic and computationally efficient segmentation methods.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Probabilistic mixture models such as Gaussian mixture models (GMM) are used to resolve point set registration problems in image processing and computer vision fields.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] For pair-wise point set registration, one point set is regarded as the centroids of mixture models, and the other point set is regarded as data points (observations).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] State-of-the-art methods are e.g. coherent point drift (CPD) and Student's t-distribution mixture models (TMM).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Mixture models are widely used in the social sciences to cluster observational data and identify latent group structure in complex, heterogeneous populations.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In studies of armed conflict, unsupervised mixture-model-based clustering has been applied to conflict event data to group observations into empirically derived conflict types without relying on predefined categories.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Such analyses reveal systematic differences across clusters in geographic, demographic, economic and infrastructural characteristics, corresponding to distinct conflict archetypes associated with different population and development profiles.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] This is one of the numerous examples of how mixture models can support data-driven classification in social science research.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Identifiability refers to the existence of a unique characterization for any one of the models in the class (family) being considered.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Estimation procedures may not be well-defined and asymptotic theory may not hold if a model is not identifiable.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Let *J* be the class of all binomial distributions with *n* = 2.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Clearly, given *p*0 and *p*1, it is not possible to determine the above mixture model uniquely, as there are three parameters (*π*, *θ*1, *θ*2) to be determined.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Consider a mixture of parametric distributions of the same class.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] be the class of all component distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Parametric mixture models are often used when we know the distribution *Y* and we can sample from *X*, but we would like to determine the *ai* and *θi* values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Such situations can arise in studies in which we sample from a population that is composed of several distinct subpopulations.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] It is common to think of probability mixture modeling as a missing data problem.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] One way to understand this is to assume that the data points under consideration have "membership" in one of the distributions we are using to model the data.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] When we start, this membership is unknown, or missing.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The job of estimation is to devise appropriate parameters for the model functions we choose, with the connection to the data points being represented as their membership in the individual model distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] A variety of approaches to the problem of mixture decomposition have been proposed, many of which focus on maximum likelihood methods such as expectation maximization (EM) or maximum *a posteriori* estimation (MAP).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Generally these methods consider separately the questions of system identification and parameter estimation; methods to determine the number and functional form of components within a mixture are distinguished from methods to estimate the corresponding parameter values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Some notable departures are the graphical methods as outlined in Tarter and Lock and more recently minimum message length (MML) techniques such as Figueiredo and Jain and to some extent the moment matching pattern analysis routines suggested by McWilliam and Loh (2009).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Expectation maximization (EM) is seemingly the most popular technique used to determine the parameters of a mixture with an *a priori* given number of components.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] This is a particular way of implementing maximum likelihood estimation for this problem.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Thus on the basis of the current estimate for the parameters, the conditional probability for a given observation *x*(*t*) being generated from state *s* is determined for each *t* = 1, …, *N* ; *N* being the sample size.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The parameters are then updated such that the new component weights correspond to the average conditional probability and each component mean and covariance is the component specific weighted average of the mean and covariance of the entire sample.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Dempster also showed that each successive EM iteration will not decrease the likelihood, a property not shared by other gradient based maximization techniques.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Moreover, EM naturally embeds within it constraints on the probability vector, and for sufficiently large sample sizes positive definiteness of the covariance iterates.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] This is a key advantage since explicitly constrained methods incur extra computational costs to check and maintain appropriate values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Theoretically EM is a first-order algorithm and as such converges slowly to a fixed-point solution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Redner and Walker (1984) make this point arguing in favour of superlinear and second order Newton and quasi-Newton methods and reporting slow convergence in EM on the basis of their empirical tests.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] They do concede that convergence in likelihood was rapid even if convergence in the parameter values themselves was not.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The relative merits of EM and other algorithms vis-à-vis convergence have been discussed in other literature.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Other common objections to the use of EM are that it has a propensity to spuriously identify local maxima, as well as displaying sensitivity to initial values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Figueiredo and Jain note that convergence to 'meaningless' parameter values obtained at the boundary (where regularity conditions breakdown, e.g., Ghosh and Sen (1985)) is frequently observed when the number of model components exceeds the optimal/true one.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] On this basis they suggest a unified approach to estimation and identification in which the initial *n* is chosen to greatly exceed the expected optimal value.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Their optimization routine is constructed via a minimum message length (MML) criterion that effectively eliminates a candidate component if there is insufficient information to support it.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In this way it is possible to systematize reductions in *n* and consider estimation and identification jointly.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] With initial guesses for the parameters of our mixture model, "partial membership" of each data point in each constituent distribution is computed by calculating expectation values for the membership variables of each data point.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] With expectation values in hand for group membership, plug-in estimates are recomputed for the distribution parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The mixing coefficients *ai* are the means of the membership values over the *N* data points.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The component model parameters *θi* are also calculated by expectation maximization using data points *xj* that have been weighted using the membership values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] With new estimates for *ai* and the *θi'*s, the expectation step is repeated to recompute new membership values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The entire procedure is repeated until model parameters converge.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] As an alternative to the EM algorithm, the mixture model parameters can be deduced using posterior sampling as indicated by Bayes' theorem.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] This is still regarded as an incomplete data problem in which membership of data points is the missing data.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] A two-step iterative procedure known as Gibbs sampling can be used.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The previous example of a mixture of two Gaussian distributions can demonstrate how the method works.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] As before, initial guesses of the parameters for the mixture model are made.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Instead of computing partial memberships for each elemental distribution, a membership value for each data point is drawn from a Bernoulli distribution (that is, it will be assigned to either the first or the second Gaussian).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The Bernoulli parameter *θ* is determined for each data point on the basis of one of the constituent distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Draws from the distribution generate membership associations for each data point.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Plug-in estimators can then be used as in the M step of EM to generate a new set of mixture model parameters, and the binomial draw step repeated.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The method of moment matching is one of the oldest techniques for determining the mixture parameters dating back to Karl Pearson's seminal work of 1894.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In this approach the parameters of the mixture are determined such that the composite distribution has moments matching some given value.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In many instances extraction of solutions to the moment equations may present non-trivial algebraic or computational problems.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Moreover, numerical analysis by Day has indicated that such methods may be inefficient compared to EM.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Nonetheless, there has been renewed interest in this method, e.g., Craigmile and Titterington (1998) and Wang.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] McWilliam and Loh (2009) consider the characterisation of a hyper-cuboid normal mixture copula in large dimensional systems for which EM would be computationally prohibitive.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Here a pattern analysis routine is used to generate multivariate tail-dependencies consistent with a set of univariate and (in some sense) bivariate moments.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The performance of this method is then evaluated using equity log-return data with Kolmogorov–Smirnov test statistics suggesting a good descriptive fit.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Some problems in mixture model estimation can be solved using spectral methods.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In particular it becomes useful if data points *xi* are points in high-dimensional real space, and the hidden distributions are known to be log-concave (such as Gaussian distribution or Exponential distribution).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Spectral methods of learning mixture models are based on the use of Singular Value Decomposition of a matrix which contains data points.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The idea is to consider the top *k* singular vectors, where *k* is the number of distributions to be learned.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The projection of each data point to a linear subspace spanned by those vectors groups points originating from the same distribution very close together, while points from different distributions stay far apart.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] One distinctive feature of the spectral method is that it allows us to prove that if distributions satisfy certain separation condition (e.g., not too close), then the estimated mixture will be very close to the true one with high probability.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Tarter and Lock describe a graphical approach to mixture identification in which a kernel function is applied to an empirical frequency plot so to reduce intra-component variance.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In this way one may more readily identify components having differing means.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] While this *λ*-method does not require prior knowledge of the number or functional form of the components its success does rely on the choice of the kernel parameters which to some extent implicitly embeds assumptions about the component structure.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Some of them can even probably learn mixtures of heavy-tailed distributions including those with infinite variance (see links to papers below).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In this setting, EM based methods would not work, since the Expectation step would diverge due to presence of outliers.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] For each *i*, generate *mi* random numbers from the *F**i* distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] In a Bayesian setting, additional levels can be added to the graphical model defining the mixture model.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] For example, in the common latent Dirichlet allocation topic model, the observations are sets of words drawn from *D* different documents and the *K* mixture components represent topics that are shared across documents.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Each document has a different set of mixture weights, which specify the topics prevalent in that document.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] All sets of mixture weights share common hyperparameters.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] A very common extension is to connect the latent variables defining the mixture component identities into a Markov chain, instead of assuming that they are independent identically distributed random variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The resulting model is termed a hidden Markov model and is one of the most common sequential hierarchical models.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Numerous extensions of hidden Markov models have been developed; see the resulting article for more information.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] The motivation for this work was provided by the zoologist Walter Frank Raphael Weldon who had speculated in 1893 (in Tarter and Lock) that asymmetry in the histogram of these ratios could signal evolutionary divergence.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Pearson's approach was to fit a univariate mixture of two normals to the data by choosing the five parameters of the mixture such that the empirical moments matched that of the model.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] While his work was successful in identifying two potentially distinct sub-populations and in demonstrating the flexibility of mixtures as a moment matching tool, the formulation required the solution of a 9th degree (nonic) polynomial which at the time posed a significant computational challenge.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Subsequent works focused on addressing these problems, but it was not until the advent of the modern computer and the popularisation of Maximum Likelihood (MLE) parameterisation techniques that research really took off.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/gaussian-mixture-model] Since that time there has been a vast body of research on the subject spanning areas such as fisheries research, agriculture, botany, economics, medicine, genetics, psychology, palaeontology, electrophoresis, finance, geology and zoology.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] A **latent variable model** is a statistical model that relates a set of observable variables (also called *manifest variables* or *indicators*) to a set of latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] Latent variable models are applied across a wide range of fields such as biology, computer science, and social science.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] It is assumed that the responses on the indicators or manifest variables are the result of an individual's position on the latent variable(s), and that the manifest variables have nothing in common after controlling for the latent variable (local independence).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] The Rasch model represents the simplest form of item response theory.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] Mixture models are central to latent profile analysis.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] In factor analysis and latent trait analysis the latent variables are treated as continuous normally distributed variables, and in latent profile analysis and latent class analysis as from a multinomial distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] The manifest variables in factor analysis and latent profile analysis are continuous and in most cases, their conditional distribution given the latent variables is assumed to be normal.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] In latent trait analysis and latent class analysis, the manifest variables are discrete.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] These variables could be dichotomous, ordinal or nominal variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/latent-variable-model] Their conditional distributions are assumed to be binomial or multinomial.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] To derive a lower bound for the marginal likelihood (sometimes called the *evidence*) of the observed data (i.e. the marginal probability of the data given the model, with marginalization performed over unobserved variables).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This is typically used for performing model selection, the general idea being that a higher marginal likelihood for a given model indicates a better fit of the data by that model and hence a greater probability that the model in question was the one that generated the data.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In particular, whereas Monte Carlo techniques provide a numerical approximation to the exact posterior using a set of samples, variational Bayes provides a locally-optimal, exact analytical solution to an approximation of the posterior.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] As in EM, it finds a set of optimal parameter values, and it has the same alternating structure as does EM, based on a set of interlocked (mutually dependent) equations that cannot be solved analytically.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] For many applications, variational Bayes produces solutions of comparable accuracy to Gibbs sampling at greater speed.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, deriving the set of equations used to update the parameters iteratively often requires a large amount of work compared with deriving the comparable Gibbs sampling equations.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This is the case even for many models that are conceptually quite simple, as is demonstrated below in the case of a basic non-hierarchical model with only two parameters and no latent variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The similarity (or dissimilarity) is measured in terms of a dissimilarity function $d(Q;P)$ and hence inference is performed by selecting the distribution $Q(\mathbf {Z} )$ that minimizes $d(Q;P)$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The most common type of variational Bayes uses the Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-divergence) of *Q* from *P* as the choice of dissimilarity function.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This choice makes this minimization tractable.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that *Q* and *P* are reversed from what one might expect.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This use of reversed KL-divergence is conceptually similar to the expectation–maximization algorithm.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The marginalization over $\mathbf {Z}$ to calculate $P(\mathbf {X} )$ in the denominator is typically intractable, because, for example, the search space of $\mathbf {Z}$ is combinatorially large.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Therefore, we seek an approximation, using $Q(\mathbf {Z} )\approx P(\mathbf {Z} \mid \mathbf {X} )$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] As the *log-evidence* $\log P(\mathbf {X} )$ is fixed with respect to Q , maximizing the final term ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ minimizes the KL divergence of Q from P .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] By appropriate choice of Q , ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ becomes tractable to compute and to maximize.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Hence we have both an analytical approximation Q for the posterior $P(\mathbf {Z} \mid \mathbf {X} )$ , and a lower bound ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ for the log-evidence $\log P(\mathbf {X} )$ (since the KL-divergence is non-negative).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The lower bound ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ is known as the (negative) **variational free energy** in analogy with thermodynamic free energy because it can also be expressed as a negative energy $\operatorname {E} _{Q}[\log P(\mathbf {Z} ,\mathbf {X} )]$ plus the entropy of Q .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The term ${\mathcal {L}}(Q)$ is also known as **Evidence Lower Bound**, abbreviated as **ELBO**, to emphasize that it is a lower (worst-case) bound on the log-evidence of the data.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The term $\zeta (\mathbf {X} )$ is often called the evidence lower bound (**ELBO**) in practice, since $P(\mathbf {X} )\geq \zeta (\mathbf {X} )=\exp({\mathcal {L}}(Q^{*}))$ , as shown above.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] By interchanging the roles of $\mathbf {Z} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {Z} _{2},$ we can iteratively compute the approximated $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} _{1})$ and $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} _{2})$ of the true model's marginals $P(\mathbf {Z} _{1}\mid \mathbf {X} )$ and $P(\mathbf {Z} _{2}\mid \mathbf {X} ),$ respectively.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Although this iterative scheme is guaranteed to converge monotonically, the converged $Q^{*}$ is only a local minimizer of $D_{\mathrm {KL} }(Q\parallel P)$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The constant in the above expression is related to the normalizing constant (the denominator in the expression above for $q_{j}^{*}$ ) and is usually reinstated by inspection, as the rest of the expression can usually be recognized as being a known type of distribution (e.g.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This creates circular dependencies between the parameters of the distributions over variables in one partition and the expectations of variables in the other partitions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An algorithm of this sort is guaranteed to converge.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The formula for the distribution's parameters will be expressed in terms of the prior distributions' hyperparameters (which are known constants), but also in terms of expectations of functions of variables in other partitions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Usually these expectations can be simplified into functions of expectations of the variables themselves (i.e. the means); sometimes expectations of squared variables (which can be related to the variance of the variables), or expectations of higher powers (i.e. higher moments) also appear.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In most cases, the other variables' distributions will be from known families, and the formulas for the relevant expectations can be looked up.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, those formulas depend on those distributions' parameters, which depend in turn on the expectations about other variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The result is that the formulas for the parameters of each variable's distributions can be expressed as a series of equations with mutual, nonlinear dependencies among the variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Usually, it is not possible to solve this system of equations directly.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, as described above, the dependencies suggest a simple iterative algorithm, which in most cases is guaranteed to converge.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An example will make this process clearer.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The following theorem is referred to as a duality formula for variational inference.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It explains some important properties of the variational distributions used in variational Bayes methods.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Theorem Consider two probability spaces $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ and $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},Q)$ with $Q\ll P$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that there is a common dominating probability measure $\lambda$ such that $P\ll \lambda$ and $Q\ll \lambda$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Let h denote any real-valued random variable on $(\Theta ,{\mathcal {F}},P)$ that satisfies $\exp h\in L_{1}(P)$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] almost surely with respect to probability measure Q , where $p(\theta )=dP/d\lambda$ and $q(\theta )=dQ/d\lambda$ denote the Radon–Nikodym derivatives of the probability measures P and Q with respect to $\lambda$ , respectively.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Consider a simple non-hierarchical Bayesian model consisting of a set of i.i.d. observations from a Gaussian distribution, with unknown mean and variance.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In the following, we work through this model in great detail to illustrate the workings of the variational Bayes method.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] For mathematical convenience, in the following example we work in terms of the precision — i.e. the reciprocal of the variance (or in a multivariate Gaussian, the inverse of the covariance matrix) — rather than the variance itself.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] We place conjugate prior distributions on the unknown mean $\mu$ and precision $\tau$ , i.e. the mean also follows a Gaussian distribution while the precision follows a gamma distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The hyperparameters $\mu _{0},\lambda _{0},a_{0}$ and $b_{0}$ in the prior distributions are fixed, given values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] They can be set to small positive numbers to give broad prior distributions indicating ignorance about the prior distributions of $\mu$ and $\tau$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that $q(\mu ,\tau )=q(\mu )q(\tau )$ , i.e. that the posterior distribution factorizes into independent factors for $\mu$ and $\tau$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This type of assumption underlies the variational Bayesian method.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The true posterior distribution does not in fact factor this way (in fact, in this simple case, it is known to be a Gaussian-gamma distribution), and hence the result we obtain will be an approximation.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In the above derivation, C , $C_{2}$ and $C_{3}$ refer to values that are constant with respect to $\mu$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that the term $\operatorname {E} _{\tau }[\ln p(\tau )]$ is not a function of $\mu$ and will have the same value regardless of the value of $\mu$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Hence in line 3 we can absorb it into the constant term at the end.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The last line is simply a quadratic polynomial in $\mu$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Since this is the logarithm of $q_{\mu }^{*}(\mu )$ , we can see that $q_{\mu }^{*}(\mu )$ itself is a Gaussian distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that all of the above steps can be shortened by using the formula for the sum of two quadratics.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The derivation of $q_{\tau }^{*}(\tau )$ is similar to above, although we omit some of the details for the sake of brevity.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Exponentiating both sides, we can see that $q_{\tau }^{*}(\tau )$ is a gamma distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In each case, the parameters for the distribution over one of the variables depend on expectations taken with respect to the other variable.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note that there are circular dependencies among the formulas for $\lambda _{N}$ and $b_{N}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Initialize $\lambda _{N}$ to some arbitrary value.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Use the current value of $\lambda _{N},$ along with the known values of the other parameters, to compute $b_{N}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Use the current value of $b_{N},$ along with the known values of the other parameters, to compute $\lambda _{N}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Repeat the last two steps until convergence (i.e. until neither value has changed more than some small amount).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It can be shown that this algorithm is guaranteed to converge to a local maximum.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Note also that the posterior distributions have the same form as the corresponding prior distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] We did *not* assume this; the only assumption we made was that the distributions factorize, and the form of the distributions followed naturally.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] It turns out (see below) that the fact that the posterior distributions have the same form as the prior distributions is not a coincidence, but a general result whenever the prior distributions are members of the exponential family, which is the case for most of the standard distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Partition the unobserved variables into two or more subsets, over which the independent factors will be derived.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] There is no universal procedure for doing this; creating too many subsets yields a poor approximation, while creating too few makes the entire variational Bayes procedure intractable.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Typically, the first split is to separate the parameters and latent variables; often, this is enough by itself to produce a tractable result.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Assume that the partitions are called $\mathbf {Z} _{1},\ldots ,\mathbf {Z} _{M}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Fill in the formula for the joint probability distribution using the graphical model.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Any component conditional distributions that don't involve any of the variables in $\mathbf {Z} _{j}$ can be ignored; they will be folded into the constant term.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Simplify the formula and apply the expectation operator, following the above example.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Ideally, this should simplify into expectations of basic functions of variables not in $\mathbf {Z} _{j}$ (e.g. first or second raw moments, expectation of a logarithm, etc.).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In order for the variational Bayes procedure to work well, these expectations should generally be expressible analytically as functions of the parameters and/or hyperparameters of the distributions of these variables.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In all cases, these expectation terms are constants with respect to the variables in the current partition.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The functional form of the formula with respect to the variables in the current partition indicates the type of distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In particular, exponentiating the formula generates the probability density function (PDF) of the distribution (or at least, something proportional to it, with unknown normalization constant).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] In order for the overall method to be tractable, it should be possible to recognize the functional form as belonging to a known distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Significant mathematical manipulation may be required to convert the formula into a form that matches the PDF of a known distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] When this can be done, the normalization constant can be reinstated by definition, and equations for the parameters of the known distribution can be derived by extracting the appropriate parts of the formula.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] When this procedure can be applied to all partitions, the result is a set of mutually linked equations specifying the optimum values of all parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] An expectation–maximization (EM) type procedure is then applied, picking an initial value for each parameter and the iterating through a series of steps, where at each step we cycle through the equations, updating each parameter in turn.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Due to all of the mathematical manipulations involved, it is easy to lose track of the big picture.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] "Analytical approximation" means that a formula can be written down for the posterior distribution.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The formula generally consists of a product of well-known probability distributions, each of which *factorizes* over a set of unobserved variables (i.e. it is conditionally independent of the other variables, given the observed data).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] This formula is not the true posterior distribution, but an approximation to it; in particular, it will generally agree fairly closely in the lowest moments of the unobserved variables, e.g. the mean and variance.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The result of all of the mathematical manipulations is (1) the identity of the probability distributions making up the factors, and (2) mutually dependent formulas for the parameters of these distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The actual values of these parameters are computed numerically, through an alternating iterative procedure much like EM.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Variational Bayes (VB) is often compared with expectation–maximization (EM).
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The actual numerical procedure is quite similar, in that both are alternating iterative procedures that successively converge on optimum parameter values.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] The initial steps to derive the respective procedures are also vaguely similar, both starting out with formulas for probability densities and both involving significant amounts of mathematical manipulations.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] However, there are a number of differences.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p01] Most important is *what* is being computed.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] In other words, $q^{*}(\mathbf {Z} )$ is a product of single-observation multinomial distributions, and factors over each individual $\mathbf {z} _{n}$ , which is distributed as a single-observation multinomial distribution with parameters $r_{nk}$ for $k=1\dots K$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] which is a standard result for categorical distributions.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] These can be converted from proportional to absolute values by normalizing over k so that the corresponding values sum to 1.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] The update equations for the parameters $\alpha _{1\dots K}$ of the variable $\mathbf {\pi }$ depend on the statistic $N_{k}$ , which depends in turn on $r_{nk}$ .
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] An M-step that uses the new value of $r_{nk}$ to compute new values of all the other parameters.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] Note that these steps correspond closely with the standard EM algorithm to derive a maximum likelihood or maximum a posteriori (MAP) solution for the parameters of a Gaussian mixture model.
[src:expectation-maximization-inference/variational-bayesian-methods-p02] This is a general result that holds true for all prior distributions derived from the exponential family.
